{
  "texts": [
    "The Hamiltonian (1) is symmetric under Z q rotations R: θ → θ + 2π q and Z 2 reflections T: θ → -θ, which obey T RT = R -1 and generate the dihedral group D q ∼ = Z q ⋊ Z 2 [15].",
    "In addition, there are the symmetries of the square lattice.",
    "We focus on even q, since odd values introduce additional, nontrivial frustration.The standard clock model (J 2 = 0) exhibits an emergent U (1) symmetry for q > 4 at intermediate temperatures [8][9][10][11][12], giving rise to a critical XY-like quasilong-range ordered (QLRO) phase, intervening between the low-temperature Z q -broken FM phase (denoted as Z +q FM [42]) and a high-temperature paramagnetic (PM) phase.",
    "Both transitions -PM to QLRO and QLRO to Z + q FM -are of the Berezinskii-Kosterlitz-Thouless (BKT) [43][44][45] type (c.f.",
    "[46]).For finite J 2, the Hamiltonian (1) reduces to the wellknown J 1 -J 2 Ising model when q = 2."
  ]
}